→| WM slots | Core slots like `^focus-level`, `^focus-parent-id` are unused |\n    57→| compare integration | `ARCKG/comparison.py`'s `compare()` is not called from the agent loop |\n    58→| predict/submit | No logic to write prediction results to the output-link |\n    59→\n    60→---\n    61→\n    62→## System Design Principles\n    63→\n    64→### ARCKG 5-Level Hierarchy\n    65→\n    66→```\n    67→TASK (T{hex})\n    68→ └── PAIR (P{n} / Pa for test)\n    69→      └── GRID (G0=input, G1=output)\n    70→           └── OBJECT (O{n})\n    71→                └── PIXEL (X{n})\n    72→```\n    73→\n    74→- Node = folder, Edge = JSON file\n    75→- Relations are lazily generated — `compare()` is called only when needed\n    76→- Comparison results are stored under `semantic_memory/`\n    77→\n    78→### SOAR Decision Cycle\n    79→\n    80→```\n    81→Each cycle:\n    82→  1. Elaborate  — Repeat ElaborationRules until fixed-point\n    83→  2. Propose    — ProductionRules collect operator candidates\n    84→  3. Select     — Choose one based on PREFERENCE_ORDER\n    85→  4. Apply      — Call operator.effect(wm)\n    86→\n    87→Impasse conditions:\n    88→  - No WM change (no-change) → create substate\n    89→  - Operator failure         → create substate\n    90→  - No candidates            → create substate\n    91→```\n    92→\n    93→### Operator Design Intent (implementation target)\n    94→\n    95→| Operator | Intent | What to write to WM |\n    96→|----------|--------|---------------------|\n    97→| `solve-task` | Top-level goal representation. No WM change → trigger no-change impasse | Nothing (intentional) |\n    98→| `deepen` | Move focus one level down | `^focus-level`, `^focus-ids` |\n    99→| `compare-within-parent` | Compare G0 vs G1 within a single PAIR | `^last-comparison` |\n   100→| `compare-siblings` | Compare sibling nodes at the same level (e.g., P0 vs P1) | `^last-comparison` |\n   101→| `note-imbalance` | Detect structural imbalance | `^imbalance`, `^imbalance-kind` |\n   102→| `extract-invariants` | Extract common patterns from comparison results | `^invariant-chunk` |\n   103→| `generalize` | Create abstract rules | Save to `procedural_memory` |\n   104→| `predict` | Apply rules to test input | Predicted grid on output-link |\n   105→| `submit` | Submit prediction → complete goal | `^goal-satisfied true` |\n   106→\n   107→**Prohibited**: Do not use TASK, PAIR, GRID, OBJECT, PIXEL directly in operator names/docstrings.\n   108→Levels are expressed only through the `^focus-level` WM slot value.\n   109→\n   110→---\n   111→\n   112→## How the Agent Solves the Problem (implementation reference)\n   113→\n   114→Below is a concrete exploration flow based on task `08ed6ac7`.\n   115→Use this as a reference to implement operators that actually perform this flow.\n   116→\n   117→### Step 1 — Receive TASK\n   118→- Load task with `ARCManager` → build ARCKG (already working)\n   119→- Inject into WM input-link with `inject_arc_task(task, wm)` (already working)\n   120→- `solve-task` operator proposed → no WM change → no-change impasse → S2 created\n   121→\n   122→### Step 2 — Check TASK properties\n   123→- `deepen` operator proposed in S2\n   124→- Write `^focus-level = \"TASK\"` to WM\n   125→- Read `E_T{hex}.json` to check TASK properties (`number_of_pairs`, etc.)\n   126→\n   127→### Step 3 — Compare with other TASKs in semantic_memory\n   128→- On first run, no other TASKs exist → this step can be skipped\n   129→- If other TASKs exist in semantic_memory, run `compare-siblings`\n   130→\n   131→### Step 4 — Descend to PAIR level\n   132→- TASK properties alone cannot achieve the goal → impasse\n   133→- `deepen` → `^focus-level = \"PAIR\"`\n   134→- Check all PAIR properties (`number_of_grids`, example vs test distinction)\n   135→\n   136→### Step 5 — Compare between PAIRs\n   137→- `compare-siblings` (P0 vs Pa)\n   138→- Result: Pa's grid_count = 1 ≠ P0's grid_count = 2\n   139→- `note-imbalance` → `^imbalance-kind = \"grid_count\"`\n   140→- Set goal: make Pa's grid_count = 2 = generate output GRID\n   141→\n   142→### Step 6 — Descend to GRID level\n   143→- `deepen` → `^focus-level = \"GRID\"`\n   144→- Compare G0 (input) vs G1 (output) within P0: `compare-within-parent`\n   145→- Call `compare()` → generate `E_P0G0-P0G1.json`\n   146→- Check GRID property (color, size, contents) differences/commonalities\n   147→\n   148→### Step 7 — Compare with other PAIR GRIDs\n   149→- `compare-siblings` (P0G0 vs P1G0, P0G1 vs P1G1)\n   150→- Discovery: all GRID sizes identical, inputs share same colors, outputs share same colors\n   151→- Conclusion: Pa's output GRID size = example output size, color = example output color\n   152→- However, contents cannot be predicted yet → new goal: predict contents\n   153→\n   154→### Step 8 — Descend to OBJECT level\n   155→- `deepen` → `^focus-level = \"OBJECT\"`\n   156→- Check all Object properties in P0G0\n   157→- Check all Object properties in P0G1\n   158→- `compare-within-parent` (P0G0 objects vs P0G1 objects, 1:1 mapping)\n   159→- Result: Object with area=9 color=5 → transformed to area=9 color=1 (score 7/8)\n   160→- Generate temporary program → apply to P0G0 → compare with P0G1\n   161→\n   162→### Step 9 — Compare OBJECTs from other PAIRs\n   163→- Repeat the same process for P1G0, P1G1\n   164→- Discovery: color=5 → color=1 pattern exists in P1 as well\n   165→- However, criteria for which Object is selected in each PAIR are needed\n   166→\n   167→### Step 10 — Extract Object selection criteria\n   168→- Search for common internal relations among transformed Objects in P0G0 and P1G0\n   169→- Discovery: transformed Object is the one with the largest area among Objects with the same color\n   170→- This becomes the selection criterion → `extract-invariants`\n   171→- `^invariant-chunk = \"select object where color=X and area=max among siblings\"`\n   172→\n   173→### Step 11 — Rule generation\n   174→- `generalize` operator\n   175→- Rule: \"Transform the color of the Object with max area among Objects with color=X to Y\"\n   176→- X, Y are values extracted from PAIR comparisons\n   177→\n   178→### Step 12 — Apply to test input\n   179→- `predict` operator\n   180→- Apply rule to Pa's G0 (input only)\n   181→- Generate output GRID\n   182→\n   183→### Step 13 — Submit\n   184→- `submit` operator\n   185→- `^goal-satisfied true`\n   186→- `run_task.py` → confirm \"CORRECT\"\n   187→\n   188→---\n   189→\n   190→## Per-Session Procedure\n   191→\n   192→### At session start\n   193→\n   194→```bash\n   195→# 1. Check previous session logs\n   196→cat logs/session_log.md | tail -50\n   197→\n   198→# 2. Check current status\n   199→python run_task.py\n   200→\n   201→# 3. Analyze errors/output, then set goals for this session\n   202→```\n   203→\n   204→### During session\n   205→\n   206→- Implement one operator or rule at a time\n   207→- After implementation, always run `python run_task.py` to verify direction\n   208→- If errors occur, analyze error messages to identify causes and fix them\n   209→\n   210→### At session end (must follow this order)\n   211→\n   212→```bash\n   213→# 1. Final run_task.py execution and capture results\n   214→python run_task.py 2>&1 | tee /tmp/session_result.txt\n   215→\n   216→# 2. Write session log (format below)\n   217→# Append to logs/session_log.md\n   218→\n   219→# 3. git add & commit & push\n   220→git add -A\n   221→git commit -m \"Session N: <one-line summary>\"\n   222→git push origin main\n   223→```\n   224→\n   225→---\n   226→\n   227→## Session Log Format\n   228→\n   229→**Append** to the file `logs/session_log.md` in the format below.\n   230→(Create the file if it does not exist)\n   231→\n   232→```markdown\n   233→---\n   234→## Session N — YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM\n   235→\n   236→### This session's goal\n   237→(What was intended)\n   238→\n   239→### Modified files\n   240→- `agent/active_operators.py` — Implemented deepen operator (reason: ...)\n   241→- `agent/rules.py` — Added siblings-ready rule (reason: ...)\n   242→\n   243→### run_task.py result\n   244→(Paste key parts of execution output)\n   245→\n   246→### Discoveries / Gotchas\n   247→(Unexpected findings, caveats, reasons for getting stuck)\n   248→\n   249→### Starting point for next session\n   250→(Stopped here, next session should do this)\n   251→```\n   252→\n   253→---\n   254→\n   255→## Implementation Priority (refer to when stuck)\n   256→\n   257→1. `agent/active_operators.py` — Implement `DeepenOperator`\n   258→   - Lower `^focus-level` WM slot by one step\n   259→   - Record list of node IDs at that level in `^focus-ids`\n   260→\n   261→2. `agent/rules.py` — Implement `top-scope-no-detail` rule\n   262→   - Condition: no `^focus-level`, `^current-task` exists\n   263→   - Propose: `deepen`\n   264→\n   265→3. `agent/active_operators.py` — Implement `CompareWithinParentOperator`\n   266→   - Call `compare()` from `ARCKG/comparison.py`\n   267→   - Write result to WM `^last-comparison`\n   268→\n   269→4. `agent/active_operators.py` — Implement `CompareSiblingsOperator`\n   270→   - Sequentially compare sibling nodes under the same parent\n   271→\n   272→5. `agent/active_operators.py` — Implement `NoteImbalanceOperator`\n   273→   - Detect DIFF items from `^last-comparison`\n   274→   - Write `^imbalance-kind` to WM\n   275→\n   276→6. `agent/active_operators.py` — Implement `ExtractInvariantsOperator`\n   277→   - Extract COMM patterns → `^invariant-chunk`\n   278→\n   279→7. `agent/active_operators.py` — Implement `PredictOperator`\n   280→   - Apply invariant + diff patterns to test input\n   281→\n   282→8. `agent/active_operators.py` — Implement `SubmitOperator`\n   283→   - Write result to output-link\n   284→   - `^goal-satisfied true`\n   285→\n   286→---\n   287→\n   288→## Key File Structure\n   289→\n   290→```\n   291→agent/\n   292→  cycle.py          ← run_cycle() — modify with caution\n   293→